Challenge 3 Questions:
5. We had to use a nested loop instead of a simple one because of the letters we had to 
include. Also we had to make a string to inlude all possible numbers and letters specified. 

6. It did increase the difficulty of cracking the password. We had to iterate through a
longer string. This made more possible combinations and we had to limit the random password 
because the computer froze since it had so many possibilities at first.

7. Similar to how the computer froze in question 6, the more characters you have the more combinations you 
have to check. This can make it take a very long time to crack the password or even freeze
your computer.

Final Challenge Questions:
8. Long passwords are the hardest to crack because they take the longest to iterate through. There
are too many combinations.

9. Companies can prevent brute force attacks by limiting the number of attempts users can make when entering 
password. They can also require two factor authentication.